Annotation.Text:
The motor on the ETC assembly is modeled as a simple electric motor.
The ETC system is separated out into an actuator and a plant model.
The actuator model consists of the electric motor, 
and the plant consists of the mechanical portions of the throttle.
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text: NOTE: If a pulse from these 2 clocks occurs at the same\ntime, the stateflow block will process the top clock first \nregardless of the scheduling outlined in the stateflow block.

Annotation.Text:
This block represents all software-based 
calculations that must be modeled. Other functions, such 
as determining engine speed from a hall-effect or magnetic
pick-up sensor that may be accomplished by a timer
processing unit (TPU) or other hardware need not be 
included here.
Annotation.name: Note2

Annotation.Text:
An explicit scheduler is used to
determine which task should be triggered first. Note 
that block execution is not user-defined in Simulink but
is user-defined (based on a top-left to bottom-right style)
from within Stateflow.
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text:
These manual switches can be used
to simulate a fault in a specific task. When
clicked, the corresponding portion
 of the controller will be enabled/disabled. 
Note that the monitor and manager must
be able to communicate to handle a fault so
disabling either of them will not change the mode
of operation.
Annotation.name: Note4

Annotation.Text:
In accordance with the Ford styleguide, various high level software components are
represented at this level as subsystems. Each subsystem is a "link" to a separate
*.mdl file that contains the archived controller. The servo_control sub-system currently
contains all the control code, but the manager should decide where the set position should
come from, the servo control should only track the set position, and the monitor should
be responsible for detecting faults.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
The merge block will accept any number of inputs.
Its output is the most recently updated of all its inputs. It is a simple
method of selecting the signal from the current mode. An alternative to 
the merge block would be the multiport switch. If the mutliport switch is used,
the Stateflow controller will have to keep track of the current mode and 
provide the mode to the switch to select the correct signal.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
Take the maximum of either human control
or the calculated throttle angle from the cruise
control. This models the driver depressing the
accelerator while cruise control is still on.
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text: During cruise control mode, the throttle command is no longer a signal from the accelerator pedal. \nIn this mode, the throttle controller acts as a regulator that tries to maintain the vehicle speed \nat some desired value that is given by the driver.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text: Apply the minimum motor voltage since cruise control is inactive.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
There are two control laws: one is a sliding mode controller
which provides good performance trying to reach the desired
throttle angle and the other is a proportional controller which is 
simple and provides good performance when the throttle angle is 
already close to the desired angle
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text: This is a simple proportional controller with an additional term to account for the spring.\nThis control is used to maintain position once the error between the \ndesired throttle angle and the actual throttle angle is small.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
This is a standard sliding mode controller design. The (known) nonlinear
dynamics are subtracted off the system and a signum or saturation
function is then used along with a tunable gain, K, to achieve the control 
objective. In this case, the control objective is to bring the error between 
the desired throttle angle and the actual throttle angle to zero.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
In the rev-limiting mode, the wheels are not slipping, but the engine speed has reached its
maximum rotational speed. The spark advance is immediately retarded to provide the quickest
reduction in engine speed, and then the throttle is closed as the fuel command is reduced to lower 
the engine speed below its redline. Note that the ETC allows for stoichiometric air-fuel ratios during
this mode since the driver's torque command is de-coupled from the engine and is being supplied here.
Once the engine speed is some value below the maximum (for hysteresis), normal operation may be resumed.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text: Apply the maximum motor current since this mode is inactive.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
When wheel slip is sensed, the driver input is essentially de-coupled from the actual throttle command.
This controller should immediately try to close the throttle (after retarding spark) to regain traction. At the same
time, the fuel command should be reduced and the air/fuel ratio can be maintained close to stoichiometric
during the traction control mode. The commanded throttle angle should be maintained as close to possible as 
the requested throttle command once traction is regained.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text: Apply the maximum motor current since this mode is inactive.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text: Compare tps volts against alpha_cmd volts\nsince they have the same range.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
One of the tps sensors may be bad. 
Let's check them against their bounds, and
then compare them against the desired throttle angle and use
the one that we think is providing the best estimate.
Annotation.name: Note2

Annotation.Text: Limit the maximum throttle angle\nduring the limp-home mode.
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text:
A failure is sensed but the vehicle can still operate in limited capacity. First, the spark advance should be reduced and the
throttle should be closed while the fuel command is being reduced. Once in a near-idle mode, the vehicle may be permitted
to operate in a "limp-home" mode. This type of fault mode may be triggered by a partial failure of the ETC. Under the limp-home mode,
the control can be sliding mode (if feedback is still available) or other PI control. 
In this mode since the powertrain dynamics are not included (i.e. spark and fuel), the normal driving
mode controllers are used, but with a limited throttle angle. Also, a tps sensor may be faulty so we need to use the "best"
estimate of the true throttle angle.
Annotation.name: Note4

Annotation.Text: This is a simple proportional controller with an additional term to account for the spring.\nThis control is used to maintain position once the error between the \ndesired throttle angle and the actual throttle angle is small.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
This is a standard sliding mode controller design. The (known) nonlinear
dynamics are subtracted off the system and a signum or saturation
function is then used along with a tunable gain, K, to achieve the control 
objective. In this case, the control objective is to bring the error between 
the desired throttle angle and the actual throttle angle to zero.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
A catastrophic failure is sensed or the ignition is off. First, the spark advance should be reduced significantly. 
Then, the throttle should be immediately closed while the fuel command is being reduced 
to zero. This type of fault mode may be triggered by a total failure of the ETC -- no response to commanded 
throttle angle.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
This is a model of the mechanical portion of the throttle valve. 
Note that the throttle valve and the electric motor used to actuate the valve 
have been separated out here into a "Actuators" and "Plant" section. 
In the vehicle model, they may be integrated into a single actuators block.
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text:
These inputs would normally come
from the powertrain sensors. This model
does not include powertrain sensors, so the
values needed for ETC control are included
as constants here. Including them as a separate block
should allow for interfacing with the powertrain models.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
Simulate a fault in one of the
throttle position sensors (e.g. a grounding
of the sensor). Currently, the model can switch
to "limp-home" mode if the two throttle position
sensors do not agree to within a given bound, but 
failure of both sensors is not detected.
Annotation.name: Note1

Annotation.Text:
The sensors block here models a redundant throttle position sensor (TPS). 
The sensor acts as a potentiometer to sense current throttle position. In general,
the sensors models may include any scaling, hysteresis, deadband, time delays, etc. introduced
by the sensors.
Annotation.name: Note2

Annotation.Text: The potentiometer is modeled as a linear signal, proportional to the \nthrottle angle, alpha. A 5V output corresponds to a fully closed throttle (alpha = 0'),\nwhile a 12V output corresponds to a completely open throttle (alpha = 90').
Annotation.name: Note3

Annotation.Text: R1: resistance required to produce a 5V signal = 0.5k ohms\nR2: resistance required to produce a 12V signal = 1.2k ohms
Annotation.name: Note4

Annotation.Text: Models sensor (LVDT or pot) on accelerator pedal.
Annotation.name: Note5

Annotation.Text: These sensors are all included in the actual powertrain model. They\nare omitted here for simplicity, but must be included for accurate vehicle simulations.
Annotation.name: Note6
